## File Type Badges

PDF and Word documents automatically show a badge:

<div class="example">
  <div class="example-preview" style="width: 100%; max-width: 500px;">
    <ArticleReferences references={[
      { title: 'Budget Report', url: '/report.pdf', type: 'document' },
      { title: 'Meeting Notes', url: '/notes.docx', type: 'document' }
    ]} />
  </div>
</div>

## Reference Interface

```typescript
interface Reference {
  title: string;
  url: string;
  type?: 'agenda' | 'minutes' | 'video' | 'document' | 'external';
  description?: string;
}
```

## Props

| Prop | Type | Default | Description |
|------|------|---------|-------------|
| `references` | `Reference[]` | required | Array of reference objects |
| `title` | `string` | `'References'` | Section title |

## Features

- **External links**: Opens in new tab with `rel="noopener noreferrer"`
- **Hover effects**: Visual feedback on link hover
- **File badges**: Shows PDF/Word badge based on file extension
- **Empty state**: Renders nothing when references array is empty
